{
  "text": "Under the shift-invariance assumption, our analysis shows how the statistical properties of an ultrasonic intensity image from an incoherent scattering medium depend on the transfer function of the system, acquisition noise, and the demodulation filter used to create the analytic signal. This analysis is made difficult by the strong nonlinearity in the intensity computation. Our approach builds on the work of Smith et al. [CITATION_1] and Wagner et al. [CITATION_2] who use a result from fourth-order Gaussian correlations [CITATION_3] . Our contribution has been to derive the intensity statistics in the context of a locally shift-invariant linear imaging system [CITATION_4] that generates the RF data from which an intensity image is computed. This allows us to present general expressions for the multivariate mean and autocovariance of the intensity signal under the Gaussian assumptions (fully developed speckle) used by Wagner et al. [CITATION_5] . We have analyzed special cases of these expressions for point statistics (mean and variance) and a stationary scattering medium (intensity point-spread function and PS).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "43266181",
    "[CITATION_2]": "22366666",
